4. Interrupted time series design analysis

4.1. Base model

### 4.2. Check for autocorrelation

The base model is naive. To make it more robust, first, I assess the correlation between the series and its time lags (autocorrelation). In both cases, ACF (correlation a time series and its lags) test shows there exits a weak seasonal trend.

4.3. Correcting autocorrelation

The new model corrects autocorrelation by accounting for the correlation between the time series data and its time lags. corARMA() function defines correlation structure. p argument specifies the autoregressive order, and q argument specifies the moving average order of the ARMA structure. I ran for loop to find the combination of p and q that yields the minimum Akaike Information Criterion (AIC).
